'''Adrar Bous''' is a [[massif]] in the [[Aïr Mountains]] on the western edge of the [[Ténéré Desert]], [[Niger]]. Archaeological research at Adrar Bous, conducted by [[J. Desmond Clark]], has produced finds spanning the Late [[Acheulean]] through to the [[Neolithic]]. Most notable are extensive remains of ritualized feasting by specialized [[Tenerian culture|Tenerian]] cattle pastoralists.<ref name="Clark & DGG">{{cite book|last1=Clark|first1=J. Desmond|last2=Gifford-Gonzalez|first2=Diane|title=Adrar Bous: archaeology of a central Saharan granitic ring complex in Niger|date=2008|publisher=Royal Museum of Central Africa, Tervuren}}</ref>

