'''Angus Konstam''' (born 2 January 1960) is a Scottish author and historian. Born in [[Aberdeen]], [[Scotland]] and raised on the [[Orkney Islands]], he now resides in [[Edinburgh]]. He has written more than 60 books on [[maritime history]], [[naval history]], [[historical atlas]]es, and other historical non-fiction.<ref name=society>{{cite web|url=http://www.societyofauthors.net/search_pages/author-detail.html?id=1771 |title=The Society of Authors |publisher=societyofauthors.net }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

== Early life ==
Although born in [[Aberdeen]], [[Scotland]], he was raised on the [[Orkney Islands]].<ref name=KonstamPDF>{{cite web|last=Konstam |first=Angus |title=About Angus |publisher=anguskonstam.com |date=June 2007 |url=http://www.anguskonstam.com/docs/biography.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=17 June 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827204428/http://www.anguskonstam.com/docs/biography.pdf |archivedate=27 August 2008 }}</ref><ref name=KonstamWebsite>{{cite web| last = Konstam| first = Angus| title = Web Site| publisher=anguskonstam.com| date = June 2009| url = http://www.anguskonstam.com/|accessdate=17 June 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090504055856/http://anguskonstam.com/| archivedate= 4 May 2009 | deadurl= no}}</ref><ref name=osprey>{{cite web|author=Mike |title=Q & A: Angus Konstam |publisher=Osprey Publishing |url=http://www.ospreypublishing.com/blog/q_a_angus_konstam/ |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614012425/http://www.ospreypublishing.com/blog/q_a_angus_konstam/ |archivedate=14 June 2011 }}</ref> In 1978, at the age of 18 he left to join the [[Royal Navy]].<ref name=KonstamPDF/><ref name=KonstamWebsite/> He received a scholarship to the [[Britannia Royal Naval College|Royal Navy College]] in [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]], and went on to study history at [[Aberdeen University]].<ref name=KonstamPDF/><ref name=prnews>{{cite web | url=https://profnet.prnewswire.com/Subscriber/ExpertProfile.aspx?ei=87709 | title=Expert Profile | publisher=prnewswire.com }}</ref> After receiving a degree, he returned to the Royal Navy and spent a year at sea, during which, he visited many places that would later be written about in his naval books including the [[Caribbean]].<ref name=KonstamPDF/> He also gained important knowledge of military service, customs, seamanship and navigation during this time.<ref name=KonstamPDF/> He then studied for a master's degree at the [[University of St. Andrews]].<ref name=KonstamPDF/><ref name=KonstamWebsite/><ref name=prnews/> During this time, he explored the new field of [[maritime archaeology]] and wrote his thesis on early [[naval artillery]].<ref name=KonstamPDF/> Two decades later this formed the basis for ''Sovereigns of the Sea'', his history of [[Renaissance]] warships.<ref name=KonstamPDF/><ref name=KonstamWebsite/>

== Career ==

=== England ===
He left the navy in 1983, and the following year he began a [[Master of Letters]] in Maritime Studies at [[St. Andrews University]], a course which combined history with maritime archaeology.<ref name=KonstamPDF/> After completing his Masters thesis on Renaissance Naval Artillery, he found a job in 1985 as a supervisor on an excavation in the [[River Thames]] near the [[Tower of London]], paid for by the [[Royal Armouries]].<ref name=KonstamPDF/> While he was working in the Royal Armouries, The Tower and the Kremlin decided to swap exhibits – a "Treasures of the Tower" being shown in Moscow while "Treasures of the Kremlin" came to London.<ref name=KonstamPDF/> At the same time the curators of both museums were encouraged to exchange information, and to examine each other's collections.<ref name=KonstamPDF/> This ended up with Konstam studying the 18th century [[Russian military]].<ref name=KonstamPDF/> A mutual colleague introduced him to a historian working for [[Osprey Publishing]], who turned out to want someone to write a book about [[Peter the Great]]'s Army.<ref name=KonstamPDF/> The result was two small (15,000-word) books which first appeared in 1993 – the first easily  accessible account of the foundation of the Russian army to appear in English.<ref name=KonstamPDF/><ref name=PTG>{{Cite book |author1=Konstam, Angus |author2=Rickman, Dave | title=Peter the Great's Army | year=1993 | publisher=Osprey Publishing | location= | isbn=978-1-85532-315-5 | pages=48}}</ref>

=== United States ===
Konstam moved to [[Key West]], Florida in 1995 and became the Chief [[Curator]] in the [[Mel Fisher Maritime Heritage Museum]].<ref name=society/><ref name=osprey/> [[Mel Fisher]] was a treasure hunter who found the wreck of the Spanish treasure [[galleon]] [[Nuestra Señora de Atocha]] off the Florida Keys.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.melfisher.org/1622.htm | title=The 1622 Fleet | publisher=melfisher.org | accessdate=12 April 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070419143524/http://www.melfisher.org/1622.htm| archivedate= 19 April 2007 | deadurl= no}}</ref> One of his jobs during this time was to create traveling exhibits which toured the United States.<ref name=KonstamPDF/> During the research for a pirate exhibition, he gained an increasing interest in the subject of 18th century [[piracy]].<ref name=KonstamPDF/> He spent six years in Key West and wrote several more books, including ''The History of Pirates (2002)'', which went on to sell over 70,000 copies.<ref name=KonstamWebsite/> As he gained more information through his research, he produced ''Piracy: The Complete History (2008)'', and then, to reach a wider audience, ''The World Atlas of Pirates (2009)''.<ref name=KonstamWebsite/>

=== Present ===
He returned to Britain in early 2001, and now resides in Edinburgh, Scotland.<ref name=KonstamPDF/><ref name=amazon>{{cite web| last = Konstam| first = Angus| title = Amazon Books Author Profile| url = https://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/AAPNAJS7Y574W|accessdate=17 June 2009}}</ref> He continues to write about naval and general history subjects. His favorite subject is the historical period of the 16th and 17th centuries.<ref name=KonstamPDF/> He currently has over 70 books in print<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anguskonstam.com/read.php|title=Angus Konstam, Historian, author and pirate expert|work=anguskonstam.com}}</ref> and is on the board of [[Society of Authors|The Society of Authors]] in Scotland and board of [[Publishing Scotland]].<ref name=society/> Konstam has also been a [[Pundit (expert)|"talking head"]] on many [[cable television|cable TV]] shows.<ref name=prnews/><ref name=ja>{{cite web|url=http://www.jennybrownassociates.com/index.php/author/angus_konstam/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080314123215/http://www.jennybrownassociates.com/index.php/author/angus_konstam/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2008-03-14 |title=Our Authors |publisher=Jenny Brown Associates }}</ref>

