{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}} [[File:Capmany - Libro del Consulad, 1791 - 088.tif|thumb|''Libro del Consulad'', [[1791]].]] '''Antonio de Capmany y Montpalau''' (24 November 1742{{snd}}Cadis, Andalusia, 14 November 1813), [[Spain|Spanish]] polygraph.
==Life== He was born at [[Barcelona]], and studied logic and humanities at the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]]-run College of Bishops in Barcelona. He entered the army and took part in the [[Spanish invasion of Portugal (1762)|1762 Spanish campaign in Portugal]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}
He retired from the army in 1770, and was subsequently elected secretary of the [[Real Academia de la Historia|Royal Academy of History]] in [[Madrid]].<ref name="EB1911">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Capmany y Montpalau, Antonio de|volume=5|page=285}}</ref>
He was elected deputy for the [[Principality of Catalonia]] by the [[Cádiz Cortes]], one of 51 deputies of Catalonia in the Constituent Assembly.
Capmany died at Barcelona on 14 November 1813. His monograph on the history of his birthplace still preserves much of its original value.<ref name="EB1911"/>
A portrait of Antonio de Campmany, by Modesto Texidor, can be found in the Consulate Room at the Llotja School in [[Barcelona]].<ref>[http://hemeroteca.lavanguardia.es/preview/2008/06/08/pagina-7/71589460/pdf.html "Multinacionales en la Llotja"], "La Vanguardia", 8 June 2008.</ref>
==Family== He married Gertrudis Marqui in Seville in 1769.
==Works== His principal works are: *''Memorias históricas sobre la marina, commercio, y artes de la antigua ciudad de Barcelona'' (4 vols 1779–1792) *''Teatro histórico-critico de la elocuencia Española'' (1786) *''Filosofía de la elocuencia'' (1776) *''Cuestiones críticas sobre varios puntos de historia económica, política, y militar'' (1807)
