'''Bulent Diken''' is a Danish [[philosopher]] and [[sociologist]] who teaches at [[Lancaster University]]. He has studied [[urban planning]] at the [[Aarhus School of Architecture]].<ref>[http://www.formerwest.org/Contributors/BulentDiken Bülent Diken]</ref> He is known for his research on [[social theory]], [[post-structuralism]], [[nihilism]], [[political philosophy]], [[urban sociology]], and [[immigration]].<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/23036152.pdf?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents Review: Immanent Aporia (A review of Nihilism by Bülent Diken)]</ref><ref>[http://tcs.sagepub.com/content/28/2/152.abstract Margins of Nihilism/Nihilisms of the Margin (A review of Nihilism by Bülent Diken)]</ref><ref>[http://www.telecommunicationsbooks.net/book/The-Culture-of-Exception-Sociology-Facing-the-Camp/9780415351225/ The Culture of Exception Sociology Facing the Camp]</ref><ref>[http://www.farjamcollection.org/docpresscoverage/Self-Orientalise,%20Iran%20Inside%20Out,%20Contemporary%20Practices.pdf Self-Orientalise, Iran Inside Out, Contemporary Practices]</ref><ref>[http://www.incore.ulst.ac.uk/services/ecrd/digests/ECRD4.pdf A review of Bülent Diken's Strangers, Ambivalence and Social Theory], reviewed by [[Ioannis Armakolas]]</ref> During 1998-1999 he was an assistant professor at [[Roskilde University]], Department of Geography.<ref>[http://mimarlikfak.artuklu.edu.tr/cv_bulentdiken/ Bülent Diken]</ref><ref>[http://criticalbravenewworld.weebly.com/summary-of-ldquohuxleyrsquos-brave-new-world-and-ndash-oursrdquo.html Summary of "Huxley's Brave New World"]</ref>
